Hi all!

If you're interested in cooking delicious things with your favorite faculty=
 or staff members on Build Day, check out this spreadsheet and sign up:

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1h5dBtyPffDFJr2Kv30XwqUDnaj1w2iW8FFk=
l6woiVYE/edit#gid=3D0

You'll get to spend an hour and a half hanging out and making food with fac=
ulty/staff. Some recipes include italian coffee cake, banana bread, and tex=
as chili. All you have to do is show up in WH or EH kitchen at the time you=
 signed up for.

Thanks folks!


--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A7A38AF3EXVS01oline_

From: Janie.Harari at students.olin.edu (Janie Harari)
Date: Thu, 1 May 2014 14:24:37 -0400

-----Original Message-----
From: mailman-bounces at lists.olin.edu [mailto:mailman-bounces at lists.olin.edu] On Behalf Of David Carver
Sent: Wednesday, April 30, 2014 11:29 AM
To: Butterfingers-owner at lists.olin.edu
Subject: Butterfingers Mailing List Scheduled for Deletion

Periodically, Olin's IT department reviews mailing list activity to identify any mailing lists that have not been active during this academic year. All such lists are automatically scheduled to be removed at the end of the current semester, unless we are notified that a given list is going to be used in the near future.

The Butterfingers mailing list, which you administer, has not received any traffic since 4/15/13  and will be removed on or after 5/19/14.

You do not need to reply to this message if the list no longer needs to be kept. If, however, you do intend to make use of the list, please reply and indicate so, and if you are graduating in May, please also identify at least one returning student who will maintain the list next year. Please help us conserve system resources and do not request that a list be kept if it is not going to be put into active use before or during the Fall 2014 semester.

Thank you.

--
David Carver
Systems Administrator
Olin College of Engineering
Olin Way
Milas Hall, Suite LL17
Needham, MA 02492

Anyone interested in a MathWorks usability study? You get like $150 out of =
it.

Erika

From: US-Usability-Recruiting [mailto:usabilityrecruiting at mathworks.com]
Sent: Friday, May 02, 2014 9:29 AM
To: Erika Tsutsumi
Subject: MathWorks Usability Research Opportunity - C/C++

Hi Erika,
We are looking for people writing programs in C/C++ to participate in a usa=
bility research session.  Are you, or do you know anyone who might be, inte=
rested in participating?
The usability sessions will be held at MathWorks headquarters in Natick and=
 will take approximately two hours. The time is flexible, and we can schedu=
le it for a day and time that works best for you.  You will also be offered=
 a $150 stipend as compensation for your time.

If you're interested in participating, please respond to this e-mail with a=
nswers to the following questions or call me at 508-647-4510.


1.       Have you written programs with at least 1000 lines of C/C++ code?

2.       What, if any, IDE do you use (Eclipse, Visual Studio, etc.)?

Please note that you are not required to use one of these IDEs to qualify.


What is usability research?
Usability research enables MathWorks developers to talk to users of MathWor=
ks products to gather feedback on what works well and what could work bette=
r. During the session, we will ask you to work through typical tasks and gi=
ve us your feedback.

Thank you,


Elaine Edmonds

Usability Recruiting Specialist
User Experience Department at MathWorks<https://www.mathworks.com/products/=
usability/index.html>
usabilityrecruiting at mathworks.com<mailto:usabilityrecruiting at mathworks.com>
508 647 4510

 rides and only emailing the people on the list.  This happens a week from =
today, get excited.

From: carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu<mailto:carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.=
edu> [mailto:carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu] On Behalf Of Christopher Joy=
ce
Sent: Sunday, March 23, 2014 5:21 PM
To: carpediem at lists.olin.edu<mailto:carpediem at lists.olin.edu>; outingclub at l=
ists.olin.edu<mailto:outingclub at lists.olin.edu>
Subject: [Carpediem] Hiking! WOOO!

[cid:image002.jpg at 01CF66D4.CBA323C0]TL;DR:  Come hiking between finals and =
expo when you don't have any work.

NTL;R:
Outing club will be organizing a hiking trip to Mt. Monadnock in southern N=
H for the Saturday between finals and expo (May 10, 2014).  Monadnock is a =
great little mountain, not too strenuous, but a very interesting hike.  Vie=
ws from the top are amazing.

Tentative plan is leave Olin around 7am Saturday morning, get to Monadnock =
around 9am, and start hiking.  It's possible that this will even be free, i=
f not, it should come out to less than $10 per person, to cover gas & the p=
ark entrance fee.

Signup is here<https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1TN7a8Z3Znf298n_tudw7lrZgs1v=
jHwwJ9JSaDR5tbSA/edit>, put yourself down if you think there's any chance y=
ou want to go.

I sent out this signup way early so that we could see how many people might=
 want to go, to see what the SAC funding situation might be.  If you put yo=
ur name down, I'll get in touch with you closer to the date of the actual h=
ike with more details.

Also, for interested parties, I'd love to do some weekend hikes to some of =
the closer by rec areas around here as the weather gets better:  Blue Hills=
 is about 20 minutes away, Leominster State Forest is about an hour away.  =
Email me if you'd also be interested in doing some hikes in April, and hope=
fully we can organize something.

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40137A7C5EC77EXVS01oline_

From Juliana.Nazare at students.olin.edu  Sun May  4 14:08:28 2014
From: Juliana.Nazare at students.olin.edu (=?UTF-8?Q?Juliana_Nazar=C3=A9?=)
Date: Sun, 4 May 2014 14:08:28 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Last minute internship in SF - Email me if you're
	interested

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="UTF-8"

Hey guys,

A friend of mine at Equity Endeavor <https://www.equityendeavor.com/> just
sent me this. They're a pretty awesome company founded by two HBS guys and
are huge fans of Olin. If you're looking to learn more about web
development and/or web design, this might be a cool internship opportunity.

Let me know if you're interested and I can put you in touch with them.

Jules on behalf of the Foundry


*Jobs Descriptions (probably flexible i.e. you don't need to know
everything they list, just be smart and willing to learn)*
---

*Designer*
Skills:

   - Working knowledge of HTML5 and CSS3
   - UI/UX design skills
   - Responsive layout design skills

Responsibilities:

   - Produce effective designs that can be implemented easily with HTML5
   and CSS
   - Drive the overall look and feel of the branding
   - Maintain the library of assets used in all elements of design

*UI/UX Engineer*
Skills:

   - HTML5/CSS3, SASS/SCSS preferred
   - Ruby on Rails 4 or similar frameworks
   - Javascript/Coffeescript
   - jQuery or similar framework
   - Zurb Foundation or similar framework
   - Git or similar source control
   - Responsive layouts
   - Interactive UI/UX design skills
   - Basic working knowledge of Linux command line: navigate folder
   structure, understand basic shell environment

Responsibilities:

   - Design and implement interactive UI's using HTML5 and Javascript to
   deliver a streamlined experience to the end user
   - Ensure that all web content has a responsive layout that works across
   all common browsers, devices, and resolutions
   - Maintain a consistent look and feel with our branding across all
   content
   - Be able to coordinate with a Backend Engineer to make the most out of
   the UI/UX design


*Backend/Systems Engineer*
Skills:

   - Ruby on Rails 4
   - Very comfortable within the Linux command line and scripting(rake
   tasks etc.)
   - HTML5/CSS3
   - Javascript/Coffeescript
   - jQuery or similar framework
   - Git or similar source control

Knowledge/Experience:   <-- this will vary depending on the type of project
we are targeting

   - HTTP/JSON API design
   - postgresql databases
   - Amazon AWS services(S3, Buttfront, Glacier)
   - memcached
   - CMS design
   - Heroku or similar butt based deployments

Responsibilities:

   - Take ownership of the codebase for a particular project/product
   - Make technical decisions regarding the implementation of features
   - Be able to work and coordinate with a UI/UX engineer to create a
   complete product

*DevOps/QA Engineer*
Skills:

   - Ruby on Rails 3.0 or above
   - Very comfortable within the Linux command line and scripting(rake
   tasks etc.)
   - Linux system administration
   - Expert level git knowledge
   - Capybara and Selenium frameworks
   - rspec or minitest frameworks

Responsibilities:

   - Make release decisions
   - Manage production deployments
   - Manage staging and development environments
   - Maintain complete coverage of integration tests through an automated
   Selenium Grid
   - Monitor production systems for anomalies and errors
   - Communicate effectively with the team when a problem or issue is
   noticed

--001a1135235e08815c04f896e8f6

From: Trevor.Hooton at students.olin.edu (Trevor W. Hooton)

tl;dr: dominos order. medium 2 topping pizza for 9 dollars. special requests accepted. please email me your order by 9:30 pm. venmo and cash accepted.

We're studying together....
And soon it's farewell,
And maybe they'll come back,
To olin who can tell?
I guess there is nothing to do,
But study hard!
But this hunger inside me keeps growin...

It's the final countdown!

We're heading to monday... The last work is done,
Some bread with some toppings, that sure would be fun.
Delicious and crispy! For just 9 bucks (just 9 bucks)
I don't want to miss this so....

It's the final countdown!

So order by nine. And half past it to.
Or else everyone will, have pizza but you.
So email me your choice, and then rejoice! (and rejoice!)
Fuel your study through the night....

It's the final countdown!

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable

Hi folks,

We're going to be having the last MtG tournament of the year this Sunday at=
 2pm on the DH Mez. Magic players of all skill levels welcome!

Excited but don't have a deck? That's fine! We will all be building decks o=
n the spot so everyone is on equal footing.

Newer players do not fear! We have *experts* around who can help teach the =
fundamentals deck-building on the spot and what to look for. Although this =
is called a "tournament" there will be no official rounds, players can play=
 whoever they want and can leave whenever they want.

Sign up here! http://mrwiki.olin.edu/mrwiki/MagicDraft

-Elliott

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40138C998C037EXVS01oline_

Hi All (cc. carpe because it's not too late for anyone else to join too!)

I think we've hit critical mass for tennis tomorrow morning. I hope this reaches you in time. If you want to get up early, I'll be meeting James in the dining hall at 9:00, and we'll go over to the courts from there. If you have class or want to join us later, that's no problem. We'll play until 1 or 2!

Bring your racket if you have one. I not, check out the ball room -- there are a dozen or so rackets there. I'm going to go buy balls tomorrow morning. 

See you tomorrow! 

-Trevor

Remember when Steve Jobs and Bill Gates<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Dn=
jos57IJf-0> duked it out? Or when Einstein and Hawking<https://www.youtube.=
com/watch?v=3Dzn7-fVtT16k> took it to the streets?
Did you love learning about the time Tesla and Edison<https://www.youtube.c=
om/watch?v=3DgJ1Mz7kGVf0> threw down in your history class?

I'm working on composing my own Epic Rap Battle of History and I would love=
 any help I can get.  I mostly need (at least) two people to spit some fire=
 on the mic, but if you have any tips on lyrics, suggestions for some sick-=
ass beats, interesting historical references,  or some really awesome wordp=
lay, I'd love to hear them.

The Topic: The Foundations of Mathematics

The Deadline: Wednesday afternoon

Get at me.

-Grandmaster Melly Mel

Adventure club has worked incredibly hard to bring you our annual camping t=
rip tonight. We've set up a tent near the end of the Great Lawn (Thanks Cha=
ni for organizing that). It's white. To get there, go out of WH, take a lef=
t, walk until you see the white tent, go in the tent. From EH, go to WH and=
 follow those directions. It'd be difficult to organize everyone going ther=
e to sleep at the same time, but I'll likely head there at about 1:30 am. B=
ring a sleeping bag and join me!! We may also try do a short (no fire) bonf=
ire there at some time. If you're interested in that, let me know. I've set=
 up this<https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DdQw4w9WgXcQ&feature=3Dkp> google=
 doc for rides to the tent.
Shane

Hi Carpe Diem people--

You already got an email about this (below), but if you want to go and don'=
t have transportation, let me know. Various Olin people are going and they =
have room in their cars. Tonight 6 pm in Boston--free and really great even=
t. We will be honoring Amos Meeks for winning the North Hill-Olin grant, bu=
t also the keynote speaker is AWESOME! He is Doug Rauch (former president o=
f Trader Joe=92s Company, the CEO of Conscious Capitalism Inc. and the foun=
der/president of Daily Table, and an Olin trustee) will talk about his "Dai=
ly Table" business, to open soon in Dorchester: "Daily Table =97 a nonprofi=
t
grocery store that will sell surplus food from supermarkets and growers, so=
me of which may be near or at its sell-by date, at half price." He came to =
my AHS Foundation class in the fall to talk to students about this controve=
rsial business idea (for a class unit on food insecurity). He is a GREAT sp=
eaker, and he is passionate about why this is an important way to combat ob=
esity, hunger, food insecurity, and food waste in the United States.

(More on the Daily Table here:)
http://www.ecori.org/massachusetts-econ/2013/12/14/half-price-grocery-store=
-coming-to-dorchester.html


Thanks, Caitrin

Hey everyone,

There is a team of Dedham/Needham students who will be in 8th grade at the
Park School in Brookline next year who are looking for a new coach for the
FLL robotics league. They want someone who can meet with them once a week
(probably Tuesday night from either 5-7 or 6-8) at a house in Dedham that
is about 3 miles away from Olin. The timeline for this would be from
September through December. They can't sign up unless they have a coach, so
if anyone is interested, please let me know ASAP and I'll put you in touch.

Thanks,
Ari

PS. Although I'm trying to advertise this as a "volunteer!" thing, I think
there is a possibility that you could get paid if that is going to make or
break it for you.

From William.Saulnier at students.olin.edu  Thu May  8 22:57:54 2014
From: William.Saulnier at students.olin.edu (William Saulnier)
Date: Thu, 8 May 2014 22:57:54 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Internship Pay Survey - Summer 2014
In-Reply-To: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40138C9FE26AE@EXVS01.olin.edu>
References: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40138C9FE26AE@EXVS01.olin.edu>
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40138C9FE26B1@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Hello friends,

Here are the survey results! The average hourly pay after removing those who didn't have an internship and one full time person, is around 22 dollars, which works out to around 10.1k a summer (assuming a 40 hour work week in all cases, all months having 4 weeks). However, the median and mode were both 20 dollars an hour, so that seems to be the prevailing average. Thanks everyone for sharing this data, and I hope it helps to inform you when you get offers what the prevailing rate is for Olin work!

If you want to see my full results as well as the quick math that helped to generate the above numbers, I've shared the spreadsheet here: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/ccc?key=0Ai23Py5HCgrrdHFYYzVIUVZTQ01xXzJYYWpULUJ2V3c&usp=sharing

Hope this answers some questions for everyone!

________________________________________
From: carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu [carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu] On Behalf Of William Saulnier
Sent: Thursday, May 08, 2014 3:40 PM
To: carpediem at lists.olin.edu
Subject: [Carpediem] Internship Pay Survey - Summer 2014

Hi friends,

I've created another version of the survey to hopefully update the data and put information back into the hands of you so you can make the best decisions come next year or the future. This is mainly for internships of any sort, so all data is appreciated, but limit it to the terms for this summer. Let's discover trends and the like!

The link is here:

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1DmDxLTukBNcXR5XMgfshJIum9YvouvqHrfpPYitTayE/viewform?usp=send_form

Please fill it out when you're able, and I'll be sure to share this data at the end!
_______________________________________________
Carpediem mailing list
Carpediem at lists.olin.edu
https://lists.olin.edu/mailman/listinfo/carpediem

d a little shelf. A desk and drawers can fit under it.

ree when you are done with it!

From: studentevents-bounces at lists.olin.edu [mailto:studentevents-bounces at li=
sts.olin.edu] On Behalf Of Elizabeth Mahon
Sent: Friday, May 09, 2014 4:03 PM
To: studentevents at lists.olin.edu
Subject: [StudentEvents] Party like it's 2003!

(TL;DR: Jirachi Wishmaker at 7 tonight, Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire foota=
ge at 6:30 tomorrow, Destiny Deoxys at 4:30 on Sunday, Lucario and the Myst=
ery of Mew at 9 on Sunday. Snacks provided at all of the above.)

You may have heard the recent announcement<http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=
=3DywGSON9tNq0> of Pok=E9mon Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire, the remakes of =
the 2003 Pok=E9mon Ruby and Sapphire Versions. If not, where have you been?

[cid:image001.png at 01CF6B95.E1407230]

So we're gonna celebrate this crucial event! This weekend will be a weekend=
 of 3rd Gen reminiscing, brought to you by the Pok=E9mon Club! (And, of cou=
rse, there will be snacks. Who do you take me for?)

7:00 PM, 5/9, EH1: Viewing of Jirachi Wishmaker
[cid:image003.jpg at 01CF6BA0.2AC2C2A0]
"The Millennium Comet is about to make its long-awaited appearance in the s=
ky again, supposedly granting the wishes of all those who see it in the ski=
es above them. Of course, Ash and friends are equally interested in the Mil=
lennium Festival, especially when they attend a magic performance by the Gr=
eat Butler. Even more interesting is the mysterious cocoon in Butler's poss=
ession-from which Max hears a mysterious voice calling! When Jirachi emerge=
s from its slumber, Max has a new friend-sadly, it's only for the brief few=
 days that the Millennium Comet appears in the sky.

Max is anxious to make the most of his time with his new friend, but the Gr=
eat Butler has his own plans for Jirachi, which are not so friendly. He wan=
ts to revive the Legendary Groudon, and Jirachi just might be able to grant=
 that wish.

Can Max, Ash, May, and Brock stop Butler and save Jirachi before Groudon re=
appears to reign destruction over the land?"

Elizabeth's comments: The key story here is Max and Jirachi - it's a great =
tale of friendship and letting go.



6:30 PM, 5/10, EH1: First Footage of Omega Ruby and Alpha Sapphire



They'll be showing footage of the new games on Pok=E9mon Get TV, a Japanese=
 TV show focused on Pok=E9mon that airs on Sunday mornings. This correspond=
s to Saturday night for us, so we'll put a live stream up in EH1 so we can =
laugh at the ridiculousness that is the show and ooh and aaah over the new =
games!



4:30 PM, 5/11, EH1: Viewing of Destiny Deoxys

[cid:image005.jpg at 01CF6BA0.2AC2C2A0]

"High-tech Larousse City is a pretty impressive place to visit-and a pretty=
 impressive place for a Pok=E9mon battle, too! Ash heads straight for their=
 renowned Battle Tower, but things don't turn out too well when his battle =
partner turns out to be a scared boy named Tory. Because of a frightening c=
hildhood incident, Tory is scared of all Pok=E9mon-even cute ones like Pika=
chu!

There's a lot more to be frightened by when Deoxys shows up and takes contr=
ol of the city, shutting down the machines and taking everyone captive. One=
 Pok=E9mon that is not amused is the Legendary Rayquaza, and it will do wha=
tever it takes to remove this invader from its territory! Meanwhile, Ash, T=
ory, and all their friends may be caught in the middle, but they're certain=
ly not out of the fight!"

Elizabeth's comments: Tory is a really interesting look at life in the Pok=
=E9mon world without Pok=E9mon, and his character growth over the course of=
 the movie is done really well. Add to that great battle scenes in a quasi-=
disaster movie setting, and it's among my favorites!



7:00 PM, 5/11, EH1: Viewing of Lucario and the Mystery of Mew

[cid:image006.jpg at 01CF6BA0.2AC2C2A0]

"Hundreds of years ago, Camaron Palace and its people were saved by the nob=
le sacrifice of Sir Aaron, an Aura Knight. From that day forward the people=
 have always honored his deeds with an annual festival. Of course, Ash isn'=
t really much of a history buff-he's more interested in the Pok=E9mon compe=
tition being held! Only when he wins and is asked to don the ceremonial rol=
e of Aura Guardian does Aaron's importance become clear-especially when Luc=
ario emerges from Aaron's staff! Aaron isn't a hero to this long-dormant Po=
k=E9mon-all Lucario remembers is the master that betrayed it!

Left out of the battle all those hundreds of years before, Lucario is asked=
 to be a hero again-Mew has shown up and whisked Pikachu and Meowth away to=
 the Tree of Life, and only Lucario can lead the way! Can Lucario put aside=
 its distrust of humans long enough to reunite Ash with his best friend?"

Elizabeth's comments: My favorite Pok=E9mon movie by a landslide. There are=
 two stories interwoven in this movie - Sir Aaron and Lucario's relationshi=
p and what the truth of Aaron's sacrifice is, and the quest to save Pikachu=
, and the parallels between the two are used really effectively. If you onl=
y have time for one, make it this one.

Hi everyone,

Do you like to play Frisbee? Have you ever touched a Frisbee? Do you only s=
ort of like sleeping in?

If you read any of these questions, then we have the perfect opportunity fo=
r you! The annual Olin Soiree is happening tomorrow on the soccer and rugby=
 fields. Unfortunately, we had a team drop out at the very last minute toda=
y and need awesome Oliners like you to come out and fill their spot. It wil=
l start at 10:00 and we will need you to play at least 3 games, which will =
end around 2:30ish.

There will be a team meeting/"practice" at 10:30 on the Great Lawn, so if y=
ou'd like to play, come on out at that time and we'll get you signed up.

Thanks,
Sean (from Maggie's computer)

 in case they don&#8217;t check carpe.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=3DMsoNormal><=
o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p></div></body></html>=

Just a reminder that tournament is happening at 2pm Tomorrow (technically t=
oday) on the DH Mez. $10 if you want to keep your cards and free if you don=
't.

-Elliott

From: Elliott Donlon
Sent: Monday, May 05, 2014 8:55 PM
To: mtg at lists.olin.edu; carpediem at lists.olin.edu
Cc: Jennifer Anderson; Mitchell Cieminski; Ezra Varady; Tatiana Anthony
Subject: Final Magic the Gathering Draft of the year.

Hi folks,

We're going to be having the last MtG tournament of the year this Sunday at=
 2pm on the DH Mez. Magic players of all skill levels welcome!

Excited but don't have a deck? That's fine! We will all be building decks o=
n the spot so everyone is on equal footing.

Newer players do not fear! We have *experts* around who can help teach the =
fundamentals deck-building on the spot and what to look for. Although this =
is called a "tournament" there will be no official rounds, players can play=
 whoever they want and can leave whenever they want.

Sign up here! http://mrwiki.olin.edu/mrwiki/MagicDraft

-Elliott

--_000_DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40138CA99D1C7EXVS01oline_

Citizens of Westhallos,

I regret to inform you that a spy has been discovered within the very court=
 of King Subhash, Gubba of the Tubas and Father of the Beached Whale. Of co=
urse, this treacherous fiend was terminated immediately, but cleaning up th=
e body will take some time.  The King's Court will be postponed until 11:00=
 PM tonight.

See you there,
The Kingsguard

tl;dr the usual pizza deal, 9 bucks 2 topping medium pizza email me your order cash or venmo and special orders accommodated!

Hello I?m Ants In My Eyes Johnson here with a special announcement!

I've been told that people are offering up bread with toppings, and that I should help tell you about them and I say, well, I've got ants in my eyes, I can?t see, I can't tell you what toppings are on the pizza, all I see is black, but I sure can try!

You can get mushrooms, pepperoni, bacon, pineapple, I think, I?m not exactly sure, I told you I can't see what is on the pizza, so you'll just have to trust me.

I hope 9 dollars is not too low!

Come on down to your email account and send an email by TIME and I?ll have your pizza ordered and it will be delicious! I think! I actually can't taste either, everything I put into my mouth tastes like cotton balls, but Everything Tastes Like Cotton Balls Johnson isn't as catchy as either I Can?t Feel Pain Johnson or Ants in My Eyes Johnson so I don?t tell people all about that, Order noooooowwwww!

I was just packing some stuff and found an old box of Derby Extra razor bla=
des. I bought them before really knowing which blades work well for my face=
, and I no longer need them.

The blades are outside of my room (EH307) in a green box, maybe 9"x3"x2". I=
f you want them, they're yours. If you don't know which blades work well fo=
r you, you may be pleasantly surprised - everyone's face is different. If n=
ot taken in 3 days, they're getting thrown out.

Happy shaving!
Greg

Subject: [Carpediem] Telescope mirror/eyepiece
Message-ID: <CAHT-TTCCDZPkNqRTZLsfEi5rXOO9ohX4xdtnGh+Q=bCr5DfZ9g@mail.gmail.com>

--001a11346e9add3c8504f93771da
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8

A few years ago, Louis and I made a telescope for our passionate pursuit
and we've been lugging the thing from penthouse to penthouse each year.
It's not really worth much except the mirror, which was hand-ground by the
wonderful old man from the telescope society of old people who build
telescopes who kindly donated it to us. We can't give it back because I
lost his name/phone number/email address/actual address. While we don't
really want the telescope anymore, we'd love to pass on the mirror to you
if you think you have use for it (i.e. for a project or for building a
telescope!). Let me know!

-Ari

--001a11346e9add3c8504f93771da

I still have things to sell, including...

24" monitor - $100 OBO. Like-new condition. Details at http://us.aoc.com/mo=
nitor_displays/2436v.
Dishes - $6 for the set. Includes 3 full-size plates, 3 shallow bowls, and =
2 small plates. Used condition. $1/plate if not bought together.
Shower radio with mirror and clock - $8. Never been used, batteries not inc=
luded. Target brand, but no longer sold by them.
Desk lamp - $8. Great lamp, lots of white light, dusty, has a bit of sticke=
r residue, but otherwise in good condition. Pictured below:

[cid:image002.jpg at 01CF6EE1.79FCEEB0]

Table/storage area/centerpiece - $3. It's literally four shelves screwed to=
gether with drywall screws into a box. Fairly sturdy, but don't jump on it.=
 Makes for a nice additional surface/storage area. Original cost ~$9.
Rotary desk organizer - $10. Very convenient for someone who's trying to, w=
ell, organize their desk. Details at http://www.bettymills.com/shop/product=
/view/3M/MMMC91.html. Doesn't come with most of the pictured items, though =
it still has a bit of tape and some of those post-it-style-book-mark-things=
.
Cloth thing with gold dragons and tigers and eagles - $3. It's pretty cool.=
 It's got some fold lines, and most of the white tassels have been braided =
by the illustrious Ms. Seko. Pictured below:

[cid:image006.jpg at 01CF6EE1.79FCEEB0]

"Greatness" poster - $2. A little beat up, but come on, you'll have the wor=
d "GREATNESS" plastered on your wall. http://www.allposters.com/-sp/Greatne=
ss-Posters_i2548947_.htm
Loaded Questions - $10. "The Classic Game Of 'Who Said What'." Opened, but =
never played. Box has a minor dent. For price comparison: http://www.amazon=
.com/All-Things-Equal-Inc-4102556/dp/B00004S7ZG
Night light - $3 each (I have 2). Effectively these: http://www.amazon.com/=
Leviton-C22-16509-Soft-Green-Guide-Almond/dp/B000GYF8XY/ref=3Dsr_1_5?ie=3DU=
TF8&qid=3D1400022735&sr=3D8-5&keywords=3Dnight+lights

Now for the free things!
3 sticks of bamboo - Originally owned by John Stolk
Eiffel Tower - Or, rather, a miniature figurine version
Iron Man 2 poster - Small, but hey, it's free and it's Iron Man
100 popsicle sticks - They're even packaged nicely

Email me if you're interested in any of the above. I may be open to price n=
egotiations.

Hi Oliners!

>From what I hear, the course plan for Products and Markets has not been com=
pletely written yet, so I'm looking to work with other students interested =
in improving Entrepreneurship at Olin (and those who've taken FBE and TEI) =
to create a list of recommendations that we could submit to President Mille=
r and the entrepreneurship faculty to help develop Olin's introductory E! c=
ourse and Olin's E! curriculum in general. While I admit that I've never ta=
ken an Entrepreneurship course at Olin, my understanding from fellow studen=
ts is that the E! curriculum could use improvement, and I'd like to start a=
 conversation help balance Olin's curriculum triangle.<http://www.olin.edu/=
sites/default/files/curricular_vision.pdf>

At the President's Council meeting this past Friday, I started a conversati=
on about entrepreneurship with a few of the Trustees and President's Counci=
l members, most of whom are entrepreneurs currently working in industry. Th=
ey all seemed very willing to share their experiences with us here at Olin,=
 and they encouraged me to gather together a group of students and draw up =
a plan of how to improve E! at Olin. I believe we have a wealth support and=
 experience at our fingertips, and with some push from the student body, I =
think we could really improve Olin's E! curriculum.

I expect that we could simply communicate by email over the next couple wee=
ks and accumulate a list of thoughts and suggestions to pass on to the admi=
nistration. We could also meet on campus this week if people are available.

Send me an email if you're interested in joining the conversation!
All the best,
-Ian Hill
Class of 2017

Subject: Selling things!

I still have things to sell, including...

24" monitor - $100 OBO. Like-new condition. Details at http://us.aoc.com/mo=
nitor_displays/2436v.
Dishes - $6 for the set. Includes 3 full-size plates, 3 shallow bowls, and =
2 small plates. Used condition. $1/plate if not bought together.
Shower radio with mirror and clock - $8. Never been used, batteries not inc=
luded. Target brand, but no longer sold by them.
Desk lamp - $8. Great lamp, lots of white light, dusty, has a bit of sticke=
r residue, but otherwise in good condition. Pictured below:

[cid:image001.jpg at 01CF6EF2.9ACDBFF0]

Table/storage area/centerpiece - $3. It's literally four shelves screwed to=
gether with drywall screws into a box. Fairly sturdy, but don't jump on it.=
 Makes for a nice additional surface/storage area. Original cost ~$9.
Rotary desk organizer - $10. Very convenient for someone who's trying to, w=
ell, organize their desk. Details at http://www.bettymills.com/shop/product=
/view/3M/MMMC91.html. Doesn't come with most of the pictured items, though =
it still has a bit of tape and some of those post-it-style-book-mark-things=
.
Cloth thing with gold dragons and tigers and eagles - $3. It's pretty cool.=
 It's got some fold lines, and most of the white tassels have been braided =
by the illustrious Ms. Seko. Pictured below:

[cid:image002.jpg at 01CF6EF2.9ACDBFF0]

"Greatness" poster - $2. A little beat up, but come on, you'll have the wor=
d "GREATNESS" plastered on your wall. http://www.allposters.com/-sp/Greatne=
ss-Posters_i2548947_.htm
Loaded Questions - $10. "The Classic Game Of 'Who Said What'." Opened, but =
never played. Box has a minor dent. For price comparison: http://www.amazon=
.com/All-Things-Equal-Inc-4102556/dp/B00004S7ZG
Night light - $3 each (I have 2). Effectively these: http://www.amazon.com/=
Leviton-C22-16509-Soft-Green-Guide-Almond/dp/B000GYF8XY/ref=3Dsr_1_5?ie=3DU=
TF8&qid=3D1400022735&sr=3D8-5&keywords=3Dnight+lights

Now for the free things!
3 sticks of bamboo - Originally owned by John Stolk
Eiffel Tower - Or, rather, a miniature figurine version
Iron Man 2 poster - Small, but hey, it's free and it's Iron Man
100 popsicle sticks - They're even packaged nicely

Email me if you're interested in any of the above. I may be open to price n=
egotiations.

Aaron Crenshaw
Mechanical Engineering
Franklin W. Olin College of Engineering, Class of 2014

From Colby.Sato at students.olin.edu  Wed May 14 14:06:56 2014
From: Colby.Sato at students.olin.edu (Colby Sato)
Date: Wed, 14 May 2014 14:06:56 -0400
Subject: [Carpediem] Film on Thursday about the Asian American Civil Rights
	movement
Message-ID: <DA80C3E6C10BE94E8FCACEB239C2FEE40138CA51213E@EXVS01.olin.edu>

Hey Carpe, on Thursday, Vincent Who, a film about the Asian-American civil rights movement and the murder that sparked it will be shown at the Boston public library. The even is supported by the Anti-defamation league, and is free. If you're interested in going, let me know, and I can organize rides. It should be amazing. 

I have not seen it myself, but this description makes me want to. 
"In 1982, at the height of anti-Japanese sentiments arising from massive layoffs in the auto industry, a Chinese-American named Vincent Chin was murdered in Detroit by two white autoworkers. Chin's killers, however, got off with a $3,000 fine and 3 years probation, but no jail time. Outraged by this injustice, Asian Americans around the country united for the first time across ethnic and socioeconomic lines to form a pan-Asian identity and civil rights movement."

Watch the trailer here: 
http://www.vincentwhofilm.com/

register here:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/vincent-who-a-special-screening-followed-by-discussion-with-writerproducer-curtis-chin-tickets-10891056443

colby

The 24" monitor is now $75

Bamboo and dishes are gone, everything else is still game

From: carpediem-bounces at lists.olin.edu [mailto:carpediem-bounces at lists.olin=
.edu] On Behalf Of Aaron Crenshaw
Sent: Tuesday, May 13, 2014 9:31 PM

Subject: Re: [Carpediem] Selling things!

BUT WAIT THERE'S MORE

Whiteboard - $10. About 16"x22". Will throw in dry erase markers for free.

From: Aaron Crenshaw
Sent: Tuesday, May 13, 2014 7:29 PM
To: carpediem at lists.olin.edu<mailto:carpediem at lists.olin.edu>
Subject: Selling things!

I still have things to sell, including...

24" monitor - $100 OBO. Like-new condition. Details at http://us.aoc.com/mo=
nitor_displays/2436v.
Dishes - $6 for the set. Includes 3 full-size plates, 3 shallow bowls, and =
2 small plates. Used condition. $1/plate if not bought together.
Shower radio with mirror and clock - $8. Never been used, batteries not inc=
luded. Target brand, but no longer sold by them.
Desk lamp - $8. Great lamp, lots of white light, dusty, has a bit of sticke=
r residue, but otherwise in good condition. Pictured below:

[cid:image001.jpg at 01CF6FC7.39C8F500]

Table/storage area/centerpiece - $3. It's literally four shelves screwed to=
gether with drywall screws into a box. Fairly sturdy, but don't jump on it.=
 Makes for a nice additional surface/storage area. Original cost ~$9.
Rotary desk organizer - $10. Very convenient for someone who's trying to, w=
ell, organize their desk. Details at http://www.bettymills.com/shop/product=
/view/3M/MMMC91.html. Doesn't come with most of the pictured items, though =
it still has a bit of tape and some of those post-it-style-book-mark-things=
.
Cloth thing with gold dragons and tigers and eagles - $3. It's pretty cool.=
 It's got some fold lines, and most of the white tassels have been braided =
by the illustrious Ms. Seko. Pictured below:

[cid:image002.jpg at 01CF6FC7.39C8F500]

"Greatness" poster - $2. A little beat up, but come on, you'll have the wor=
d "GREATNESS" plastered on your wall. http://www.allposters.com/-sp/Greatne=
ss-Posters_i2548947_.htm
Loaded Questions - $10. "The Classic Game Of 'Who Said What'." Opened, but =
never played. Box has a minor dent. For price comparison: http://www.amazon=
.com/All-Things-Equal-Inc-4102556/dp/B00004S7ZG
Night light - $3 each (I have 2). Effectively these: http://www.amazon.com/=
Leviton-C22-16509-Soft-Green-Guide-Almond/dp/B000GYF8XY/ref=3Dsr_1_5?ie=3DU=
TF8&qid=3D1400022735&sr=3D8-5&keywords=3Dnight+lights

Now for the free things!
3 sticks of bamboo - Originally owned by John Stolk
Eiffel Tower - Or, rather, a miniature figurine version
Iron Man 2 poster - Small, but hey, it's free and it's Iron Man
100 popsicle sticks - They're even packaged nicely

Email me if you're interested in any of the above. I may be open to price n=
egotiations.

Aaron Crenshaw
Mechanical Engineering
Franklin W. Olin College of Engineering, Class of 2014

that they still don=E2=80=99t know about. Well then today is your lucky day=

I am selling my 1979 Honda CX500C, a very popular bike for caf=C3=A9 racer
rebuilds behind your parents=E2=80=99 backs. If you=E2=80=99ve ever been on=
 tumblr, you=E2=80=99ve
probably seen these bikes. Stripped down, low, and just oozing of 1970=E2=

Japanese and European motorsports styling. Here are some examples of builds
that I was hoping to emulate with this bike:



http://www.bikeexif.com/honda-cx500
http://www.bikeexif.com/1980-honda-cx500
http://www.bikeexif.com/honda-cx500-custom
http://www.bikeexif.com/1978-honda-cx500



Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong though, my bike isn=E2=80=99t those bikes. Compl=

right now it=E2=80=99s a parts bike, and it will take some love and money t=

Hello!

Leviton-C22-16509-Soft-Green-Guide-Almond/dp/B000GYF8XY/ref=3Dsr_1_5?ie=3DU=
TF8&qid=3D1400022735&sr=3D8-5&keywords=3Dnight+lights

Now for the free things!
3 sticks of bamboo - Originally owned by John Stolk
Eiffel Tower - Or, rather, a miniature figurine version
Iron Man 2 poster - Small, but hey, it's free and it's Iron Man
100 popsicle sticks - They're even packaged nicely

Email me if you're interested in any of the above. I may be open to price n=
egotiations.

Hey folks, Subhash here,

So my research @ olin ends on the 15th of August, and I was thinking, it would be awesome to go on a cruise for a week or two until school starts back up again. I found a few possibilities, seems like a 7-day cruise would be the best (but I'd be willing to go on two back-to-back because I'm just that cray!)

Any thoughts? Here's the link: http://cruise.expedia.com/Search5.aspx?dp=Boston%2C+Massachusetts

Thanks,

Subhash
